<DOC><DOCNO> AP900522-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-90 2034EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-22 0341</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0355</SECOND><HEAD>Texas-Sized Thunderstorms and Record Northeast Cold</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Thunderstorms battered the Texas Gulf Coast with rain, hail anda tornado Tuesday, while the northeast was chilled with a recordcold snap.   In Arkansas, where torrential weekend rains produced seriousflash flooding, the Ouachita River was significantly above floodstage early Tuesday and near crest at Arkadelphia in thesouth-central part of the state.   The degree of flooding is expected to decrease significantly asthe crest moves downstream.   Snow fell across northern Maine at noon, and the morning wasunseasonably cool in much of New England and eastern New York.   Rainshowers extended over the central coast of New England.   Showers also were scattered over northern Minnesota, easternNorth Dakota, southeastern South Dakota and northeast Nebraska, andfrom southwest Washington across western Oregon and northernCalifornia.   Showers and thunderstorms reached from central Virginia acrossWest Virginia, northwestern North Carolina, northeast Tennessee andeastern Kentucky. There also were storms over the northern andcentral portion of the Florida peninsula and the Florida panhandle.   And storms hit the lower and central Gulf Coast in Texas, wherea tornado touched down west of Port O'Connor at about noon. Smallhail and almost two inches of rain fell at nearby Palacios between2 p.m. and 3 p.m. EDT.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 1.28 inches in Victoria, Tex., an dan inch at CapeHatteras, N.C.   A cold front moved across the Pacific northwest, south-centralOregon and the northern coast of California toward the PacificOcean.   The colder temperatures were expected to bring snow to themountains of northern California.   The forecast for Wednesday included rain from northernCalifornia to the northwest, showers from the central to thenorthern Rockies and for New York, New England, Wisconsin andeastern Nebraska.   The low temperature for the nation Tuesday morning was 31degrees at Cutbank, Mt. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m.EDT ranged from 34 degrees at Houlton, Me., to 96 degrees atPhoenix, Ariz.</TEXT></DOC>